### Release Notes

<details>
<summary>oracle/helidon (io.helidon.applications:helidon-se)</summary>

### [`v4.0.0`](https://togithub.com/oracle/helidon/blob/HEAD/CHANGELOG.md#400)

[Compare Source](https://togithub.com/oracle/helidon/compare/3.2.3...4.0.0)

We are pleased to announce the release of Helidon 4.0.0. The big news in Helidon 4.0.0 is the introduction of Helidon Níma -- a ground up webserver implementation based on JDK Project Loom virtual threads. With Helidon 4 you get the high throughput of a reactive server with the simplicity of thread-per-request style programming.

The Helidon SE API in 4.0.0 has changed significantly from Helidon 3. The use of virtual threads have enabled these APIs to change from asynchronous to blocking. This results in much simpler code that is easier to write, maintain, debug and understand. Existing Helidon SE code will require modification to run on these new APIs. For more information see the [Helidon SE Upgrade Guide](https://helidon.io/docs/v4/#/se/guides/upgrade\_4x).

Helidon 4 supports MicroProfile 6. This means your existing Helidon MP 3.x applications will run on Helidon 4 with only minor modifications. And since Helidon’s MicroProfile server is based on the new Níma WebServer you get all the benefits of running on virtual threads. For more information see the [Helidon MP Upgrade Guide](https://helidon.io/docs/v4/#/mp/guides/upgrade\_4x).

New to Helidon? Then jump in and [get started](https://helidon.io/docs/v4/#/about/prerequisites).

Java 21 is required to use Helidon 4.0.0.

pull_request.title: Rails 7 config updates
pull_request.body:
I noticed a dramatic drop in the req/s for Rails after the 7 -> 7.1 upgrade. So I've made a few changes:

Changes to the config.yml that effect the Docker configuration:
- Added `RAILS_ENV` as production just in case it the fallback to `RACK_ENV` wasn't working as expected.
- Decreased logging for production by setting `RAILS_LOG_LEVEL` to `fatal`. Reducing logging should make a significant difference.

In the `Rails` test:
- Inheriting from `ActionController::Base` makes the app perform more closely to how it would if it were rendering views, so I aligned the configuration in the `config/application.rb` to match that expectation.

In the new `Rails-api` test:
- Reset the controller to inherit from the `ActionController::API` so this omits the rendering modules that normally get included into the `ActionController::Base` class
- Added some suggested middleware deletions from Rack that aren't required with an API-only Rails app


This should give a much better picture for anyone trying to understand the differences between a normal Rails app and an API-only Rails app (or just the API version of their app if they use the `ActionController::API` for their API controller base.
